{
  "The electron configuration of oxygen (Z=8) is:": "",
  "1s² 2p⁶": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p²": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁴": "",
  "Oxygen has 8 electrons: 1s² (2) + 2s² (2) + 2p⁴ (4) = 8. The 2p sublevel has 3 orbitals; by Hund's rule, the first 3 electrons fill singly, then the 4th pairs up in one orbital.": "",
  "The Aufbau principle states that electrons fill:": "",
  "All orbitals at the same time": "",
  "Highest energy orbitals first": "",
  "Lowest energy orbitals first": "",
  "Randomly": "",
  "Aufbau means 'building up' in German. Electrons fill 1s first, then 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, etc. This order minimizes the atom's total energy.": "",
  "Hund's rule states that electrons in the same sublevel:": "",
  "Skip orbitals": "",
  "Have the same spin when paired": "",
  "Occupy orbitals singly before pairing": "",
  "Always pair up first": "",
  "Like bus passengers sitting alone before doubling up, electrons fill each degenerate orbital singly (with parallel spins) before any pairing occurs. This minimizes electron-electron repulsion.": "",
  "The Pauli exclusion principle states that:": "",
  "Orbitals can hold 3 electrons": "",
  "No two electrons in the same orbital can have the same spin": "",
  "Electrons always spin up": "",
  "Electrons have no spin": "",
  "Each orbital holds a maximum of 2 electrons with opposite spins (+½ and -½). This means no two electrons in an atom can share all four quantum numbers (n, l, ml, ms).": "",
  "The electron configuration of sodium (Z=11) is:": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3p¹": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 2d¹": "",
  "1s² 2s² 3s²": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹": "",
  "Sodium has 11 electrons. After filling 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ (10 electrons), the 11th goes into 3s. The lone 3s electron is easily lost, making sodium highly reactive.": "",
  "Noble gas shorthand for chlorine (Z=17) is:": "",
  "[Ar] 3s² 3p⁵": "",
  "[He] 3s² 3p⁵": "",
  "[Ne] 3s² 3d⁵": "",
  "[Ne] 3s² 3p⁵": "",
  "Chlorine (17e) = [Ne](10e) + 3s²(2e) + 3p⁵(5e). The noble gas shorthand uses the previous noble gas ([Ne] for period 3 elements) in brackets to replace the core electrons.": "",
  "Which element has the configuration 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶?": "",
  "Argon (Z=18)": "",
  "Neon": "",
  "Potassium": "",
  "Chlorine": "",
  "Counting the electrons: 2+2+6+2+6 = 18 electrons, which matches argon (Z=18). Argon is a noble gas with a complete octet in its outer shell (3s² 3p⁶).": "",
  "What is the electron configuration of carbon (Z=6)?": "",
  "1s² 2s⁴": "",
  "1s⁶": "",
  "Carbon has 6 electrons: 1s² fills first (2e), then 2s² (2e), then 2p² (2e). By Hund's rule, the 2 electrons in 2p occupy separate orbitals with parallel spins.": "",
  "In the Aufbau filling order, which orbital fills before 3d?": "",
  "3p": "",
  "4s": "",
  "4d": "",
  "4p": "",
  "The filling order is: ...3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, 4p... The 4s orbital fills before 3d because it has lower energy due to greater penetration toward the nucleus.": "",
  "The noble gas shorthand for iron (Z=26) is:": "",
  "[Ar] 4s² 4p⁶": "",
  "[Ne] 3d⁶ 4s²": "",
  "[Ar] 3d⁸": "",
  "[Ar] 3d⁶ 4s²": "",
  "Iron (26e) = [Ar](18e) + 3d⁶(6e) + 4s²(2e) = 26. As a transition metal, iron's partially filled 3d sublevel allows it to form Fe²⁺ (lose 4s²) and Fe³⁺ (lose 4s² + one 3d).": "",
  "What is electron configuration?": "",
  "How fast electrons move around the nucleus, measured by their kinetic energy in electron volts": "",
  "The specific arrangement of electrons in an atom's orbitals, written with sublevel notation (e.g., 1s² 2s² 2p⁶)": "",
  "The shape of the atom as determined by the outermost occupied orbital and its angular geometry": "",
  "The number of protons in an atom that defines the element's position on the periodic table": "",
  "Electron configuration tells us exactly how electrons are distributed among energy levels and sublevels. It predicts chemical properties, bonding behavior, and magnetic properties of elements.": "",
  "What is noble gas shorthand notation?": "",
  "A way to write the molecular formula of noble gases showing their complete outer electron shell occupancy": "",
  "An abbreviated electron configuration using the nearest preceding noble gas in brackets to represent core electrons": "",
  "Writing only the s electrons of an atom while ignoring all p, d, and f sublevel electron contributions": "",
  "The short form of a noble gas's name as it appears in the periodic table of the chemical elements": "",
  "Instead of writing 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹ for sodium, we write [Ne] 3s¹. The [Ne] represents the first 10 electrons, and we only write the remaining valence configuration.": "",
  "What is the diagonal rule (Madelung's rule)?": "",
  "A way to calculate atomic mass": "",
  "A rule that electrons move diagonally between orbitals": "",
  "A diagram showing the order in which orbitals are filled: 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, 4p...": "",
  "A rule about drawing diagonal lines on the periodic table": "",
  "The diagonal rule helps remember the Aufbau filling order. Write sublevel columns (1s, 2s 2p, 3s 3p 3d, 4s 4p 4d 4f...) and draw diagonal arrows to get the sequence.": "",
  "What does the superscript in '2p⁴' represent?": "",
  "The number of electrons in that sublevel (4 electrons in the 2p sublevel)": "",
  "The energy level number that indicates how far the orbital is from the nucleus": "",
  "The number of orbitals available within that sublevel for electron occupancy": "",
  "The spin of the electrons indicating their clockwise or counterclockwise rotation": "",
  "In electron configuration notation, the number (2) is the energy level, the letter (p) is the sublevel type, and the superscript (⁴) is the electron count in that sublevel.": "",
  "What are core electrons vs. valence electrons in configuration terms?": "",
  "They are the same thing — both terms describe all the electrons an atom possesses regardless of which shell they occupy": "",
  "Core electrons are located in the nucleus alongside the protons, while valence electrons orbit in the outermost energy level": "",
  "Valence electrons are always in s orbitals only and never occupy p, d, or f sublevels in any atom's ground state configuration": "",
  "Core electrons are the inner filled shells (represented by the noble gas symbol); valence are the outermost electrons written after": "",
  "For sodium [Ne] 3s¹: the 10 core electrons ([Ne] = 1s² 2s² 2p⁶) are in inner shells and don't participate in bonding. The 1 valence electron (3s¹) determines sodium's chemistry.": "",
  "What is an excited state electron configuration?": "",
  "A configuration with extra electrons added beyond the atom's normal count, creating a negatively charged anion": "",
  "The normal configuration of an atom at rest, following all three rules (Aufbau, Pauli, and Hund's rule)": "",
  "A configuration where one or more electrons have been promoted to a higher energy orbital than the ground state": "",
  "An atom that has lost all its electrons through complete ionization, leaving only the bare nucleus": "",
  "When energy is absorbed (heat, light), an electron can jump to a higher sublevel. For example, excited lithium might be 1s² 2p¹ instead of ground state 1s² 2s¹. It's unstable and will emit a photon to return.": "",
  "What is a ground state electron configuration?": "",
  "The lowest-energy arrangement of electrons following Aufbau, Pauli, and Hund's rules": "",
  "The configuration of grounded (charged) atoms": "",
  "When all electrons are in the highest energy levels": "",
  "When an atom has no electrons": "",
  "The ground state is the most stable configuration. All electrons are in the lowest available orbitals. This is what we normally write as the electron configuration of an element.": "",
  "What is an isoelectronic species?": "",
  "Isotopes of the same element that have different numbers of neutrons but identical proton counts": "",
  "Atoms with the same number of protons in their nuclei, making them the same chemical element": "",
  "Atoms or ions that have the same electron configuration (e.g., Na⁺, Ne, and F⁻ all have 10 electrons)": "",
  "Elements in the same group of the periodic table that share similar valence electron arrangements": "",
  "Na⁺ (11p, 10e), Ne (10p, 10e), and F⁻ (9p, 10e) are isoelectronic — all have the configuration 1s² 2s² 2p⁶. They have identical electron arrangements despite different nuclear charges.": "",
  "What is the electron configuration of a calcium ion (Ca²⁺)?": "",
  "[Ne] 3s² — same as magnesium (12 electrons)": "",
  "[Ar] 4s² — retaining both s electrons (20 total)": "",
  "[Ar] 3d² — with two d electrons remaining (20 total)": "",
  "[Ar] — same as argon (18 electrons)": "",
  "Calcium (Z=20) is [Ar] 4s². When it forms Ca²⁺, it loses both 4s electrons, leaving 18 electrons with the same configuration as argon: 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶.": "",
  "Why is chromium's configuration [Ar] 3d⁵ 4s¹ instead of [Ar] 3d⁴ 4s²?": "",
  "The 4s orbital doesn't exist for chromium": "",
  "A half-filled d sublevel (3d⁵) is extra stable, so one 4s electron shifts to 3d": "",
  "Chromium follows the normal Aufbau rule": "",
  "Chromium has only 23 electrons": "",
  "Half-filled (d⁵) and fully filled (d¹⁰) d sublevels have extra stability from electron exchange energy. Chromium 'promotes' one 4s electron to achieve 3d⁵ — a notable exception to the Aufbau principle.": "",
  "A student writes nitrogen's configuration as 1s² 2s² 2p³ with all three 2p electrons in one orbital. What is wrong?": "",
  "Hund's rule requires the 3 electrons to occupy separate 2p orbitals with parallel spins before pairing": "",
  "There is nothing wrong with this": "",
  "The Pauli principle allows 3 electrons per orbital": "",
  "Nitrogen only has 2 electrons": "",
  "The 2p sublevel has 3 orbitals. With 3 electrons, each one occupies a separate orbital (↑ ↑ ↑) per Hund's rule, minimizing repulsion. Pauli's principle also limits each orbital to 2 electrons maximum.": "",
  "A chemistry student must determine how many unpaired electrons iron has. Given Fe: [Ar] 3d⁶ 4s², how many are unpaired?": "",
  "6 — all six 3d electrons are unpaired because the d sublevel has six available orbitals": "",
  "0 — all electrons in both the 3d and 4s sublevels are fully paired with opposite spins": "",
  "4 — the 5 d orbitals fill singly first (5 electrons), then the 6th pairs in one orbital": "",
  "2 — only the two 4s electrons are unpaired while all six 3d electrons form three pairs": "",
  "The 3d sublevel has 5 orbitals. With 6 electrons: first 5 fill singly (↑↑↑↑↑), then the 6th pairs (↑↓↑↑↑↑). The 4s² electrons are paired. Total unpaired: 4 in 3d. This makes iron paramagnetic.": "",
  "A forensic scientist identifies an unknown element with configuration [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² 5p². What element is it?": "",
  "Tin (Sn, Z=50) — a metalloid in Group 14 with 4 valence electrons": "",
  "Krypton (Kr, Z=36) — a noble gas in Group 18 with 8 valence electrons": "",
  "Lead (Pb, Z=82) — a heavy metal in Group 14 with 4 valence electrons": "",
  "Silver (Ag, Z=47) — a transition metal in Group 11 with 1 valence electron": "",
  "Count: [Kr](36) + 4d¹⁰(10) + 5s²(2) + 5p²(2) = 50 electrons = tin (Sn). Tin's 4 valence electrons (5s² 5p²) put it in Group 14, like carbon and silicon above it.": "",
  "A fluorescent light works because mercury vapor atoms absorb electrical energy and then emit light. In terms of electron configuration, what happens?": "",
  "The nucleus emits radiation as protons rearrange themselves into lower energy nuclear configurations inside atoms": "",
  "Electrons jump from ground state to excited state, then release photons as they fall back to lower energy levels": "",
  "Mercury atoms split apart into individual protons and neutrons, releasing binding energy as visible photons": "",
  "Electrons leave the mercury atoms permanently and collide with gas molecules, generating heat and colored light": "",
  "Electricity excites mercury's electrons to higher energy levels (excited state). When they return to ground state, they emit UV photons. The phosphor coating on the glass converts UV to visible light.": "",
  "A student is confused why potassium (Z=19) starts filling 4s before 3d. Using electron configuration, the answer is:": "",
  "The 4s orbital is lower in energy than 3d in neutral atoms, so the Aufbau principle places the 19th electron in 4s": "",
  "The 3d sublevel doesn’t exist for potassium because d orbitals only become available at atomic numbers above 21": "",
  "The 4s and 3d sublevels have the same energy in potassium, so the electron randomly chooses one of the two": "",
  "Potassium skips energy level 3 entirely because its nucleus is too large to support third-shell electrons": "",
  "K is [Ar] 4s¹, not [Ar] 3d¹. The 4s orbital penetrates closer to the nucleus than 3d, making it lower energy for neutral atoms. This is why Period 4 starts with K (4s¹) and Ca (4s²) before the transition metals.": "",
  "A materials scientist studies why copper is such an excellent conductor. Copper's unusual configuration [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s¹ contributes because:": "",
  "The single 4s electron is loosely held and moves freely, facilitating electrical current flow": "",
  "Copper has no electrons": "",
  "Copper's f orbitals conduct electricity": "",
  "The full 3d sublevel blocks conductivity": "",
  "Copper promotes one 4s electron to complete its 3d¹⁰. The resulting single 4s electron is delocalized in metallic bonding, enabling excellent electrical conductivity (second only to silver).": "",
  "Transition metals form colorful compounds (e.g., CuSO₄ is blue). This is linked to their electron configuration because:": "",
  "Partially filled d orbitals absorb specific wavelengths of visible light, and we see the complementary color": "",
  "Colors come from the nucleus, which emits photons of different frequencies depending on the number of protons": "",
  "The s orbitals produce color by vibrating at optical frequencies when transition metals form ionic compounds": "",
  "All metals are colored because their metallic bonding always absorbs ultraviolet light and reflects visible light": "",
  "In transition metal compounds, d-d electron transitions absorb specific photon energies. The remaining wavelengths that pass through give the compound its color. Zinc (full 3d¹⁰) compounds are colorless.": "",
  "When iron forms Fe³⁺, which electrons are removed first?": "",
  "The 1s electrons": "",
  "Three 3d electrons: [Ar] 3d³ 4s²": "",
  "The 4s electrons are removed first, then one 3d electron: [Ar] 3d⁵": "",
  "Core electrons from 2p": "",
  "Although 4s fills before 3d, when transition metals ionize, 4s electrons are removed first (they are farther from the nucleus in the ion). Fe → Fe²⁺ [Ar]3d⁶ → Fe³⁺ [Ar]3d⁵. Note Fe³⁺ has a stable half-filled d⁵.": "",
  "A medical test uses paramagnetic contrast agents in MRI scans. Gadolinium (Gd³⁺) is used because it has 7 unpaired electrons. Its configuration is [Xe] 4f⁷. Why is this exceptionally stable?": "",
  "Seven unpaired f electrons form a half-filled 4f sublevel, which has extra stability from exchange energy": "",
  "All lanthanides have the same number of unpaired electrons": "",
  "The 4f sublevel only holds 7 electrons": "",
  "Gadolinium has no electrons": "",
  "Like the d⁵ exception in chromium, the half-filled f⁷ sublevel is extra stable. Gd³⁺'s 7 unpaired electrons create a strong magnetic moment, making it ideal for MRI contrast enhancement.": "",
  "A chemistry teacher shows that Na⁺, Mg²⁺, and Al³⁺ all have 10 electrons. She asks what electron configuration they share. The answer is:": "",
  "1s¹⁰ — all ten electrons packed into the first energy level’s single orbital": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² — twelve electrons filling through the third energy level": "",
  "Each has a different configuration because their nuclear charges are all different": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶ — the same as neon, making them isoelectronic with Ne": "",
  "Na⁺ (11-1=10e), Mg²⁺ (12-2=10e), and Al³⁺ (13-3=10e) all have 10 electrons arranged as 1s² 2s² 2p⁶. They are isoelectronic with neon, which explains their stability — they achieved a noble gas configuration.": ""
}